IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: Patrol Vehicle E-15 is equipped with an in car camera. Dash Camera:https://mdsp.evidence.com/axon/evidence?evidence_id=485ddb368cf84cbfa4c415975181eb22partner_id=5ed6a168304e40eb9a0cfb1a226ef1a1 Body Worn Camera:https://mdsp.evidence.com/axon/evidence?evidence_id=9444516aeb374bd298fd158117128d06partner_id=5ed6a168304e40eb9a0cfb1a226ef1a1 In Car Camera:https://mdsp.evidence.com/axon/evidence?evidence_id=6f18d38b8d59449aa2f10e854a8abbd9partner_id=5ed6a168304e40eb9a0cfb1a226ef1a1 Crime: Driving Under the Influence Weather: Clear and 75 degrees Defendant: Latia Aushae Parks Date of Birth: 5/27/1994 Date of Arrest: 7/18/2023 Time of Arrest: 2254 hours License#: MD-10273619679 DUI #: 23-54-146 DUI Citation #: 2Q70URM Subsequent Offender: No Accident Involved: No CERTIFICATES AND TRAINING: * I am trained to administer standardized field sobriety tests through the Maryland State Police and National Highway Traffic Safety Administration. *I have successfully completed the Advanced Roadside Impairment Driving Enforcement course through the Maryland State Police. NARRATIVE: Phase #1 - Vehicle In Motion: On 7/18/23 at approximately 2241 hours, I TFC Eckrich, was on routine patrol in the area of Roger St and Kendall St when I observed a white Nissan bearing Maryland registration 5DT4324 traveling on Roger St. The vehicle appeared to be traveling above the posted speed limit. I activated my Kustom Golden Eagle radar and obtained a speed of 41 mph in a posted 25 mph zone. The vehicle then approached the stop sign located at Roger St and E Lincoln Ave. The vehicle failed to make a complete stop at the stop sign. As the vehicle continued on Roger St, I observed the vehicle swerve over the center line, causing its left side tires to completely go over the line. I activated my emergency equipment and initiated a traffic stop in the area of Roger St and Bethel St. Phase #2 - Personal Contact I exited my patrol vehicle and made contact with the driver who was later identified by her Maryland drivers license as LATIA AUSHAE PARKS (B/F 5/27/94). I advised Parks the reason for the stop and that she was being audibly and visually recorded. I observed Parks eyes to be bloodshot and glassy. While speaking with Parks I detected the strong odor of alcoholic beverage coming from within the vehicle. I asked Parks multiple times for her registration card and she would try to change the conversation. I asked Parks how much she had to drink and she stated she had a shot earlier. I returned to my patrol vehicle and relayed Parks information to MSP Salisbury. Phase #3 - Pre Arrest Screening I returned to Parkss vehicle and asked her to step out of the vehicle. While speaking with Parks outside of the vehicle, I again detected the strong odor of alcoholic beverage but this time it was coming from Parkss breath and person. Based on my observations, I advised Parks I would be conducting standardized field sobriety tests. Parks voluntarily agreed to perform Standardized Field Sobriety Tests I asked Parks a standard series of questions for pre-screening prior to performing the Standardized Field Sobriety test. Visual check of inside of Parks mouth: Clear Do you wear contacts or glasses: No Any medication: No Recreational drugs: No Any injuries or disabilities: No Parks then voluntarily agreed to submit to the Standardized Field Sobriety Tests and I began with the Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus Test. Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus I explained the Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus test to Parks and asked her if she understood the test. Parks stated that she understood the test and I began. Resting Nystagmus: No Equal Tracking: Yes Equal Pupil Size: Yes Lack of smooth pursuit in both eyes Distinct and sustained Nystagmus at maximum deviation in both eyes Onset of nystagmus prior to 45 degrees present in both eyes. Vertical Nystagmus: Yes Total Horizontal Gaze NystagmusClues:6 out of 6 Walk and Turn Weather: Clear Surface: Level surface, clear of any debris. Parks removed her shoes for the test I instructed Parks into the instructional phase. During my demonstration of the test Parks could not maintain her balance and broke heel to toe. I instructed Parks to return to the instructional position. I asked Parks if she understood the test, and she stated that she understood the instructions. Instructional Phase: -Cannot maintain balance Walking stage 1st 9: -Missed heel to toe on steps 5 and 6 -Stepped off line on steps 1 and 2 -Incorrect number of steps: 16 Turn: Incorrect: turned around in one motion instead of taking a series of small steps as instructed Walking stage 2nd 9: -Missed heel to toe on steps 6 through 9 -Raised arms for balance on every step -Stepped off line on step 3 -Incorrect number of steps: 10 Total Walk and Turn Clues: 6 of 8 One Leg Stand I next explained and demonstrated the One Leg Stand test to Parks. I asked Parks if she understood the test and she stated she did.Parks picked up her right foot for the test. Seconds 1-10: Swayed from side to side Raised arms for balance Put foot down at 3 second mark Seconds 11-20: Swayed from side to side Raised arms for balance Put foot down at 13 second mark Seconds 21-30: Swayed from side to side Put foot down at 23 second mark Raised arms for balance Total One Leg Stand Clues:3 of 4 Preliminary Breath Test Parks was offered the preliminary breath test. Parks refused to submit to preliminary breath test. Arrest and Transport Based on the following, I had reason to believe Parks was driving a motor vehicle under the influence of alcohol: * Eyes unusually glassy. * Strong odor of an alcoholic beverage coming from inside the vehicle. * Strong odor of an alcoholic beverage coming from her breath and person. * My observed signs of impairment as she performed standard field sobriety tests. * Admitted to drinking alcoholic beverage. I placed Parks under arrest for driving under the influence of alcohol at 2254 hours. I placed Parks into the front passenger seat of my patrol vehicle. I then entered my patrol vehicle at which time I detected the strong odor of an alcoholic beverage that was not present in my vehicle prior to placing Parks into my vehicle. 20 Minute Observation Period: I transported Parks to the Maryland State Police Salisbury barrack for processing. I read the MVA DR-15 advice of rights in English to Parks. Parks stated she would submit to the intoximeter test and signed the DR-15 at 2315 hours.S/Tpr Wilkins, a certified intoximeter operator administered the test at 2326 hours. Parkss breath specimen was found to contain an alcohol concentration of .15 grams of alcohol per 210 liters of breath. Parks was given copies of all pertinent paperwork and released to a sober driver. All events occurred in Wicomico County Maryland.
